'''Sir John Banham''' (born 22 August 1940)<ref name="BD">"Birthdays", ''[[The Independent]]'', 22 August 1994 (Banham was 54 on this date)</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] business leader.  He has been the chairman of [[Whitbread]], a major brewer since 2000, and is also chairman of ECI Ventures and [[Johnson Matthey]].

== Biography ==
He was raised in [[Cornwall]], where his father worked as a [[surgeon]] and his mother a [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS) administrator, and was educated at [[Charterhouse School]], and [[Queens' College, Cambridge]], where he gained a first class degree in Natural Sciences.<ref name="Cope">Cope, Nigel (2001) "[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/sir-john-banham-is-this-the-most-confident-man-in-britain-672780.html  Sir John Banham: Is this the most confident man in Britain?]", ''[[The Independent]]'', 4 June 2001, retrieved 2010-02-01</ref> He worked at the Foreign Office for two years before moving to Reed International and then [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey and Co]].<ref name="Cope" />

He was the first controller of the [[Audit Commission]] from 1983 to 1987, and was then Director General of the [[Confederation of British Industry]] from 1987 to 1992.<ref name="Cope" /><ref name="Cope1995" />  In 1992 he became chairman of the [[Local Government Commission for England (1992)|Local Government Commission for England]] that led to a large-scale local government reform in [[England]].<ref name="LGC">"[http://www.lgcplus.com/news/banham-in-derbyshire-deal-with-government/1629183.article BANHAM IN DERBYSHIRE DEAL WITH GOVERNMENT]", ''[[Local Government Chronicle]]'', 7 January 1994, retrieved 2010-02-01</ref>  He was [[knight]]ed in 1992.

He was chairman of [[Tarmac Limited|Tarmac]] from 1994 to 1999, and the chairman of [[Kingfisher plc]] from 1995 to 2001.<ref name="Cope1995">Cope, Nigel (1995) "[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/sir-john-banham-to-head-kingfisher-1577923.html Sir John Banham to head Kingfisher]", ''[[The Independent]]'', 16 October 1995, retrieved 2010-02-01</ref><ref name="Griffiths">Griffiths, Katherine (2001) "[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/banham-quits-but-denies-kingfisher-rift-683962.html Banham quits but denies Kingfisher rift]", ''[[The Independent]]'', 7 May 2001, retrieved 2010-02-01</ref> He became the chairman of [[Johnson Matthey]] in April 2006.<ref name="Chem">"John Banham", ''[[Chemistry & Industry]]'', May 1, 2006</ref> He has also acted as chairman of [[West Country Television]] and as a non-executive director of both [[National Westminster Bank]] and [[National Power]].<ref name="Cope1995" />

